    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="431"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d431">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/693</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs at
                            Nanking</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Chinese Legation</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="65" xml:id="d431fn65">Copy of telegram transmitted to the Department by
                        the Chinese Legation, December 14, 1932.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-14">December 14,
                            1932</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The news of the resumption of diplomatic relations with Soviet Russia was
                    favorably commented in the Chinese press. There was a nation-wide expression of
                    satisfaction and the government was praised.</p>
                <p>Commenting on the United States government’s unwillingness to participate in the
                    conciliation committee, <persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Chiu Kuo Jih Pao</hi>
                    </persName> says in his editorial today that the reason seems to lie in the
                    contrary views maintained by <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SSJ1">Sir John
                        Simon</persName> and Secretary <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1"
                        >Stimson</persName> regarding the Manchurian question. It would appear that
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SSJ1">Simon</persName> is inclined to
                    acquiesce in the <hi rend="italic">fait accompli</hi> whereas <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1">Stimson</persName> stands for the
                    non-recognition of any status created by the force of arms.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
